&gt;     &lt;option value=&quot;on&quot;/&gt;
&gt;    &lt;/select&gt;
&gt;   &lt;/doc&gt;
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt;   PUT /resource?status=on
&gt;   =&gt; 200
&gt;   &lt;doc&gt;
&gt;    &lt;select name=&quot;status&quot;&gt;
&gt;     &lt;option value=&quot;loading-microcode&quot; selected=&quot;true&quot;/&gt;
&gt;     &lt;option value=&quot;off&quot;/&gt;
&gt;    &lt;/select&gt;
&gt;   &lt;/doc&gt;

Ah, the light just went on (no pun intended).  I now get what you and Hugh
are talking about.  I was thrown by the HTML representation, but viewing it
in light of the added context, it makes a lot of sense.  I get resource
state and application state bundled nicely into one concise chunk.  Not only
that, but by formulating the representation in HTML, I get operational
semantics to boot.  Potentially adding HTML forms might even bring more to
the party...

Thanks.
